Here is an example of blocking read interrupted by signal, with EINTR handling:

```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main() {
    int status;
    pid_t pid;

    pid = fork();
    if (pid == 0) {
        // Child process
        printf("Child process started.\n");
        sleep(10);
        printf("Child process finished.\n");
        exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
    } else {
        // Parent process
        printf("Parent process started.\n");
        waitpid(pid, &status, 0);
        printf("Parent process finished.\n");
        exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
    }
}
```

In this example, the parent process creates a child process using the `fork()` function. The child process sleeps for 10 seconds and then exits. The parent process waits for the child process to finish using the `waitpid()` function.

