Here's an example of how you can create a middleware in Laravel that blocks users whose IP is not in an array:

```php
namespace App\Http\Middleware;

use Closure;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;

class IpCheck
{
    public function handle($request, Closure $next)
    {
        $allowedIps = ['192.168.1.1', '192.168.1.2'];

        if (in_array($request->ip(), $allowedIps)) {
            return $next($request);
        }

        return response('You are not authorized to access this resource. Please contact your administrator for more information. ', 403);
    }
}
```

In this example, we've created a middleware class called `IpCheck`. This middleware checks if the user's IP address is in an array of allowed IPs. If the user's IP is not in the allowed IPs array, the middleware returns a 403 Forbidden response.

To use this middleware, you'll need to register it in your `app/Providers/RouteServiceProvider.php` file. Here's an example of how you can register this middleware:

```php
use App\Http\Middleware\IpCheck;

class RouteServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider
{
    public function boot()
    {
        $this->app->bind('middleware', function ($app) {
            return new IpCheck;
        });
    }
}
```

With this middleware registered, you can now use it in your routes by adding the `middleware` attribute to your route definition. Here's an example of how you can use this middleware in a route:

```php
Route::get('/dashboard', 'DashboardController@index')->middleware('ip.check');
```

With this route definition, any requests to the `/dashboard` URL will be checked by the `IpCheck` middleware before the request is handled by the `DashboardController@index` action. If the user's IP address is not in the allowed IPs array, the middleware will return a 403 Forbidden response.

